This collection presents an expanded notion of spectatorship with a more dynamic sense of embodied and performed engagement with places. The approach resonates with ideas in anthropology, sociology, and geography on performance, invented traditions, constructed places and traveling cultures. Contributions highlight the often contradictory, contested and paradoxical constructions of landscape and community involved both in tourist attractions and among tourists themselves. The collection examines many different practices, ranging from the energetic pursuit of adventure holidays to the reading of holiday brochures. It illustrates different techniques of seeing the landscape and a variety of ways of creating and performing the local. Chapters thus demonstrate the mutual entanglement of practices, images, conventions, and creativity. They chart these global flows of people, texts, images, and artefacts. Case studies are drawn from diverse types of tourism and destination focused around North America, Europe, and Australasia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aTourismxSocial aspects. 0aTourism. 7aTravel / General.2bisacsh  aTravel and Tourism, Theory and Methodology.1 aBell, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoissevain, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaney, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman, Simon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCrang, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrang, Mike, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCrouch, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEade, 